r is\nnoted hae not yet appeared.\nThe heghtbhouse tender arrived here\nvesterday afternoon and gave ap added\nattracrion alongside the U. 3. S.\n\"\u2018Grebe\u2019\u2019 with its bright lights last night.\nN\nCorrespondence\nEdaitor St. Croix Avis\nDear Sir:\nI had the good fortune (o\nfind a place among the members of that\nreinarkable confraternity of antagorists\nthe Opera Comique. Every variety of\nphilosophical and political opinion was\npresented and expressed there, Most\nof my colleagues were of one sort or an\nother, atd however kind and friendly\nthey might be, I,- {homas L. Branningan\nEsquire, the man without a ragof a\nlabel to cover himse'f with, could not\nfail to have some uneasy feelings which\nmust have besat the historical fox,\nwhen after leaving the trap, in which\nhis tail remained, he presented him\nself to bhis normally elongated com\npanions,\nWhy I was christened Thomas, Ido\nr.ot know, but it is a curious chance that\nmy parents should have fixed for my\nusual denomination upon the name of\nthat particular Apostle with whom al\nways felt most sympathy,\nOs a!l the Creatures on earth, man is\nthe most stuck up, he arrogates every\nthing to himself, and because he can\ncross tle Atlantic in afew hours, he\nthicks he certres the Universe. Wiih\nthat splendid magnanim ty characteris\ntie of the race, man would rather pitch\n$60.000 00 into chaos, than for amo\nment entertain the idea that heisa\nhumibug., and of no use whatever.\nAfter a'l the jelly fish may be a worthi\ner fe:low than the best of us\nIdo not of course insist on the rever\nsion of the jelly fish; I do not know that\nI am urving reversion to anything, but\nam saying right here that myriads\nof facilities are given for acquiring po\nlitical igrorance in this country.\nshould open by saying{that I, IThomas\nL. Branningan Esquire, after a long and\npainfui investigation, in caucus with my\ncollesgues, considered myself fully qual\nified.\nUpon gauging the depth of my owvn\nknowledge, and considering ccnscien\ntiously the capacity of my acquaint\nances, came ihe conclusion that no\nman know personally in that confra\nternity had so close a personal intimacy\nwith ignorance than myself. To be\nsure there 1s nothing in the Constitu\ntion \u00a2f things to justify thiz imperti\nnence, {or the proceedings are usually\nopened with prayer.\nSo far as know man is the only be\ning capable of doing evil or offending\nheaven His absence may by nature be\nconsidered very good company. What\never part of this earth he can handle\nor move he has turned topsy turvy.\nOne day earth will turn on bhim and\nwipe him out.\nBRANNINGAN.\nOctober 15, 1930.\nPOST OFFICE NOTES.\nReleased weekly by B R. Larsen, P. M.\nChristiansted, V. 1. for the imformation\nand guidance of the mailing public.\nConstructive criticism and suggestions\nlooking toward increasing the efficiency\nof service wi'l be gladly received and if\npracticable given consideration.\nWalter Field Co., Chicago, has writ-","height":"18403","width":"15283"}}
